Thanks <@UV23JHEJY> its really helpful, Really Thanks

Hey people - not sure this is possible, hoping on of you more hubl savvy developers know how to do this. I’m trying to pass rejectattr(‘property’) as an argument to map. My syntax is off. Anyone know how to accomplish this. I know there are other routes, but want to keep it as simple as possible:

```{% set lines =
quote1.associated_objects.line_items|escape|map("rejectattr('extended_asset_description_2')") %}```
What is currently being returned and what you would like to be returned

Currently getting an array with a null value: [null]. I’m trying to eliminate a key value pair from an array of objects.

I want my return value to be the same array of objects, but without the extended_asset_description_2.

It was more of a curiosity than anything else. I could just loop through and create a new array. Just figured there was a simple syntax error that would allow me to do it this way if corrected.
So rejectattr will actually eliminate all objects (from an array) that don't fit the criteria

Unfortunately I just read through all the docs and couldn't find a way to do it, the map filter really only wants to map one property not multiple (unlike JS obviously), HubL (Jinjava) doesn't have a native delete function either so you can't do it that way
But like you said you can always just create a new array (this is definitely annoying though)

Yep, definitely seems I’d completely misunderstood the function of the rejectattr filter. I wasn’t studying the output initially because I was developing locally. Assumptions will be the death of me.

I appreciate the help. This is the first time I’ve come on here in months, and based on your contributions alone, it seems to have become a much more useful resource.  You’re bringing a ton of value to the devs in this space.
